    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-21T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-21T13:00:00-05:00" n="318"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d318">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">330/5–2154: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Belgium</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Alger</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brussels</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-21T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 21, 1954—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>900. Department telegram 1135 May 19 (sent <gloss target="#t_USUN1">Usun</gloss>
                    567). Belgian Government has not approached Embassy re UNSC seat. Local press
                    has, however, carried BeLGA report under New York dateline stating Belgium will
                    be candidate for <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> seat and will have support
                    Scandinavian countries and Netherlands.</p>
                <p>In consideration this question, Embassy is of opinion that
                        <persName>Spaak</persName>’s<note n="1" xml:id="d318fn1">
                        <persName>Paul Henri Spaak</persName>, former Belgian Premier and Foreign
                        Minister.</note> re-emergence on the world scene as Foreign Minister and his
                    effectiveness in supporting major policy objectives sought by US cannot be
                    over-emphasized. It seems desirable in our opinion to overlook no means of
                    enhancing his and Belgian prestige and we believe that support of Belgian
                    candidacy for <gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> seat is warranted in light of
                    foregoing unless there are other overriding considerations of which Embassy is
                    not aware.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Alger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
